==English==
===Etymology===
The phrase "to go postal" first entered common parlance in American in the mid-1990s following a rash of incidents, mostly gun violence, perpetrated by stressed U.S. Postal Service workers. Mail delivery is notorious for being a high-stress job, and so the term carries connotations of losing control under pressure and usually refers to irrational acts of violence.

===Verb===
'''go postal'''
# ([[euphemism]]) To behave in a [[stressed]] or [[irrational]] manner, especially in the [[workplace]].